& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Amyloidosis is a group of conditions defined by extracellular deposition of insoluble proteins that can lead to multiorgan dysfunction and failure. The systemic form of the disease is often associated with a plasma cell dyscrasia but may also occur in the setting of chronic inflammation, long-term dialysis, malignancy, or multiple hereditary conditions. Localized forms of the disease most often involve the skin, tracheobronchial tree, and urinary tract and typically require tissue sampling for diagnosis, as they may mimic many conditions including malignancy at imaging alone. Advancements in MRI and nuclear medicine have provided greater specificity for the diagnosis of amyloidosis involving the central nervous system and heart, potentially obviating the need for biopsy of the affected organ in certain circumstances. Specifically, a combination of characteristic findings at noninvasive cardiac MRI and skeletal scintigraphy in patients without an underlying plasma cell dyscrasia is diagnostic for cardiac transthyretin amyloidosis. Histologically, the presence of amyloid is denoted by staining with Congo red and a characteristic apple green birefringence under polarized light microscopy. The imaging features of amyloid vary across each organ system but share some common patterns, such as soft-tissue infiltration and calcification, that may suggest the diagnosis in the appropriate clinical context. The availability of novel therapeutics that target amyloid protein fibrils such as transthyretin highlights the importance of early diagnosis.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021210006">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021210006">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Amyloid deposition in the bowel in four patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mural stratification with submucosal soft-tissue infiltration (arrows) in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and small bowel amyloidosis. (b, c) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image (b) shows diffuse mural edema of the right colon (arrows) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Corresponding colonoscopy image (c) shows multiple small irregularly shaped and shallow ulcers (arrowheads). Biopsy results confirmed focal amyloid deposition in the muscularis mucosae. (d) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen from a gastric biopsy with extensive pale pink amorphous material throughout the lamina propria (arrow), consistent with the presence of amyloid, in a 41-year-old man with lysozyme amyloidosis. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100). (e) Photomicrographs show characteristic histopathologic findings at high-power microscopy, with the presence of amyloid (arrows), including positive staining with Congo red (left) and apple green birefringence under polarized light (right), in a 72-year-old woman with colonic amyloidosis (Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig1a.jpeg" height="1011" width="1281" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Amyloid deposition in the bowel in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mural stratification with submucosal soft-tissue infiltration (arrows) in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and small bowel amyloidosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> shows diffuse mural edema of the right colon (arrows) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Corresponding colonoscopy image <b>(c)</b> shows multiple small irregularly shaped and shallow ulcers (arrowheads). Biopsy results confirmed focal amyloid deposition in the muscularis mucosae. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen from a gastric biopsy with extensive pale pink amorphous material throughout the lamina propria (arrow), consistent with the presence of amyloid, in a 41-year-old man with lysozyme amyloidosis. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrographs show characteristic histopathologic findings at high-power microscopy, with the presence of amyloid (arrows), including positive staining with Congo red (left) and apple green birefringence under polarized light (right), in a 72-year-old woman with colonic amyloidosis (Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="Amyloid deposition in the bowel in four patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mural stratification with submucosal soft-tissue infiltration (arrows) in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and small bowel amyloidosis. (b, c) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image (b) shows diffuse mural edema of the right colon (arrows) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Corresponding colonoscopy image (c) shows multiple small irregularly shaped and shallow ulcers (arrowheads). Biopsy results confirmed focal amyloid deposition in the muscularis mucosae. (d) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen from a gastric biopsy with extensive pale pink amorphous material throughout the lamina propria (arrow), consistent with the presence of amyloid, in a 41-year-old man with lysozyme amyloidosis. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100). (e) Photomicrographs show characteristic histopathologic findings at high-power microscopy, with the presence of amyloid (arrows), including positive staining with Congo red (left) and apple green birefringence under polarized light (right), in a 72-year-old woman with colonic amyloidosis (Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig1b.jpeg" height="1011" width="1132" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Amyloid deposition in the bowel in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mural stratification with submucosal soft-tissue infiltration (arrows) in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and small bowel amyloidosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> shows diffuse mural edema of the right colon (arrows) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Corresponding colonoscopy image <b>(c)</b> shows multiple small irregularly shaped and shallow ulcers (arrowheads). Biopsy results confirmed focal amyloid deposition in the muscularis mucosae. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen from a gastric biopsy with extensive pale pink amorphous material throughout the lamina propria (arrow), consistent with the presence of amyloid, in a 41-year-old man with lysozyme amyloidosis. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrographs show characteristic histopathologic findings at high-power microscopy, with the presence of amyloid (arrows), including positive staining with Congo red (left) and apple green birefringence under polarized light (right), in a 72-year-old woman with colonic amyloidosis (Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic" aria-label="Amyloid deposition in the bowel in four patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mural stratification with submucosal soft-tissue infiltration (arrows) in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and small bowel amyloidosis. (b, c) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image (b) shows diffuse mural edema of the right colon (arrows) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Corresponding colonoscopy image (c) shows multiple small irregularly shaped and shallow ulcers (arrowheads). Biopsy results confirmed focal amyloid deposition in the muscularis mucosae. (d) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen from a gastric biopsy with extensive pale pink amorphous material throughout the lamina propria (arrow), consistent with the presence of amyloid, in a 41-year-old man with lysozyme amyloidosis. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100). (e) Photomicrographs show characteristic histopathologic findings at high-power microscopy, with the presence of amyloid (arrows), including positive staining with Congo red (left) and apple green birefringence under polarized light (right), in a 72-year-old woman with colonic amyloidosis (Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig1c.jpeg" height="1003" width="1290" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Amyloid deposition in the bowel in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mural stratification with submucosal soft-tissue infiltration (arrows) in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and small bowel amyloidosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> shows diffuse mural edema of the right colon (arrows) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Corresponding colonoscopy image <b>(c)</b> shows multiple small irregularly shaped and shallow ulcers (arrowheads). Biopsy results confirmed focal amyloid deposition in the muscularis mucosae. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen from a gastric biopsy with extensive pale pink amorphous material throughout the lamina propria (arrow), consistent with the presence of amyloid, in a 41-year-old man with lysozyme amyloidosis. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrographs show characteristic histopathologic findings at high-power microscopy, with the presence of amyloid (arrows), including positive staining with Congo red (left) and apple green birefringence under polarized light (right), in a 72-year-old woman with colonic amyloidosis (Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic" aria-label="Amyloid deposition in the bowel in four patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mural stratification with submucosal soft-tissue infiltration (arrows) in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and small bowel amyloidosis. (b, c) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image (b) shows diffuse mural edema of the right colon (arrows) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Corresponding colonoscopy image (c) shows multiple small irregularly shaped and shallow ulcers (arrowheads). Biopsy results confirmed focal amyloid deposition in the muscularis mucosae. (d) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen from a gastric biopsy with extensive pale pink amorphous material throughout the lamina propria (arrow), consistent with the presence of amyloid, in a 41-year-old man with lysozyme amyloidosis. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100). (e) Photomicrographs show characteristic histopathologic findings at high-power microscopy, with the presence of amyloid (arrows), including positive staining with Congo red (left) and apple green birefringence under polarized light (right), in a 72-year-old woman with colonic amyloidosis (Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig1d.jpeg" height="999" width="1125" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Amyloid deposition in the bowel in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mural stratification with submucosal soft-tissue infiltration (arrows) in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and small bowel amyloidosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> shows diffuse mural edema of the right colon (arrows) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Corresponding colonoscopy image <b>(c)</b> shows multiple small irregularly shaped and shallow ulcers (arrowheads). Biopsy results confirmed focal amyloid deposition in the muscularis mucosae. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen from a gastric biopsy with extensive pale pink amorphous material throughout the lamina propria (arrow), consistent with the presence of amyloid, in a 41-year-old man with lysozyme amyloidosis. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrographs show characteristic histopathologic findings at high-power microscopy, with the presence of amyloid (arrows), including positive staining with Congo red (left) and apple green birefringence under polarized light (right), in a 72-year-old woman with colonic amyloidosis (Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1e" class="graphic" aria-label="Amyloid deposition in the bowel in four patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mural stratification with submucosal soft-tissue infiltration (arrows) in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and small bowel amyloidosis. (b, c) Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image (b) shows diffuse mural edema of the right colon (arrows) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Corresponding colonoscopy image (c) shows multiple small irregularly shaped and shallow ulcers (arrowheads). Biopsy results confirmed focal amyloid deposition in the muscularis mucosae. (d) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen from a gastric biopsy with extensive pale pink amorphous material throughout the lamina propria (arrow), consistent with the presence of amyloid, in a 41-year-old man with lysozyme amyloidosis. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100). (e) Photomicrographs show characteristic histopathologic findings at high-power microscopy, with the presence of amyloid (arrows), including positive staining with Congo red (left) and apple green birefringence under polarized light (right), in a 72-year-old woman with colonic amyloidosis (Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig1e.jpeg" height="999" width="2624" aria-labelledby="fig1e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1e</span>. Amyloid deposition in the bowel in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows mural stratification with submucosal soft-tissue infiltration (arrows) in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma and small bowel amyloidosis. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(b)</b> shows diffuse mural edema of the right colon (arrows) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Corresponding colonoscopy image <b>(c)</b> shows multiple small irregularly shaped and shallow ulcers (arrowheads). Biopsy results confirmed focal amyloid deposition in the muscularis mucosae. <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen from a gastric biopsy with extensive pale pink amorphous material throughout the lamina propria (arrow), consistent with the presence of amyloid, in a 41-year-old man with lysozyme amyloidosis. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×100). <b>(e)</b> Photomicrographs show characteristic histopathologic findings at high-power microscopy, with the presence of amyloid (arrows), including positive staining with Congo red (left) and apple green birefringence under polarized light (right), in a 72-year-old woman with colonic amyloidosis (Congo red stain; original magnification, ×400).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig1e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. (a) Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. (b) Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. (c) Axial fused 18F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. (d) Axial fused 18F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. (e) Multiple projection views from 18F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in d show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). (f) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig2a.jpeg" height="1510" width="1256" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. <b>(d)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. <b>(e)</b> Multiple projection views from <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in <b>d</b> show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. (a) Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. (b) Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. (c) Axial fused 18F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. (d) Axial fused 18F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. (e) Multiple projection views from 18F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in d show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). (f) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig2b.jpeg" height="1510" width="1237" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. <b>(d)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. <b>(e)</b> Multiple projection views from <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in <b>d</b> show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic" aria-label="Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. (a) Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. (b) Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. (c) Axial fused 18F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. (d) Axial fused 18F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. (e) Multiple projection views from 18F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in d show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). (f) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig2c.jpeg" height="1510" width="1210" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. <b>(d)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. <b>(e)</b> Multiple projection views from <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in <b>d</b> show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic" aria-label="Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. (a) Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. (b) Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. (c) Axial fused 18F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. (d) Axial fused 18F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. (e) Multiple projection views from 18F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in d show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). (f) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig2d.jpeg" height="1559" width="1194" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. <b>(d)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. <b>(e)</b> Multiple projection views from <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in <b>d</b> show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2e" class="graphic" aria-label="Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. (a) Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. (b) Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. (c) Axial fused 18F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. (d) Axial fused 18F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. (e) Multiple projection views from 18F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in d show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). (f) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig2e.jpeg" height="1559" width="2554" aria-labelledby="fig2e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2e</span>. Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. <b>(d)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. <b>(e)</b> Multiple projection views from <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in <b>d</b> show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig2e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2f" class="graphic" aria-label="Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. (a) Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. (b) Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. (c) Axial fused 18F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. (d) Axial fused 18F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. (e) Multiple projection views from 18F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in d show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). (f) Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig2f.jpeg" height="1348" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig2f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2f</span>. Cerebral amyloid deposition in different patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial maximum intensity projection (MIP) susceptibility-weighted image shows numerous punctate foci of susceptibility (arrowheads), consistent with microhemorrhages in a 57-year-old man with CAA. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted gradient-echo MR image shows biopsy-proven occipital hematoma (arrow) due to CAA mimicking a brain metastasis in a 70-year-old woman with papillary serous carcinoma of the peritoneum. <b>(c)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-florbetapir PET/CT image shows abnormal cortical tracer uptake (arrows), consistent with the presence of amyloid-β plaques in a 79-year-old man with AD. <b>(d)</b> Axial fused <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/MR image shows hypometabolism in the bilateral superior parietal lobes (dashed outline) in a 53-year-old man with AD and vascular amyloid deposition. <b>(e)</b> Multiple projection views from <sup>18</sup>F-FDG PET/CT three-dimensional surface-rendered imaging in the same patient as in <b>d</b> show symmetric hypometabolism in the posterior cingulate cortex and precuneus (arrows). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph shows a histopathologic specimen of CAA with vascular deposition of amyloid (pale pink material, arrows), with adjacent hemorrhage and hemosiderin deposition (*) in a 70-year-old woman with CAA.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig2f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Left orbital amyloidosis in a 63-year-old man. (a) Coronal gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows asymmetric enlargement of the left extraocular muscles (arrows), as well as ill-defined enhancement in the intraconal space of the left orbit (arrowhead). (b) Axial T2-weighted MR image shows mild proptosis of the left orbit (arrow). The patient underwent treatment with fractionated stereotactic radiation therapy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig3a.jpeg" height="1571" width="1494" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Left orbital amyloidosis in a 63-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Coronal gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows asymmetric enlargement of the left extraocular muscles (arrows), as well as ill-defined enhancement in the intraconal space of the left orbit (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows mild proptosis of the left orbit (arrow). The patient underwent treatment with fractionated stereotactic radiation therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Left orbital amyloidosis in a 63-year-old man. (a) Coronal gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows asymmetric enlargement of the left extraocular muscles (arrows), as well as ill-defined enhancement in the intraconal space of the left orbit (arrowhead). (b) Axial T2-weighted MR image shows mild proptosis of the left orbit (arrow). The patient underwent treatment with fractionated stereotactic radiation therapy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig3b.jpeg" height="1571" width="1448" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Left orbital amyloidosis in a 63-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Coronal gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows asymmetric enlargement of the left extraocular muscles (arrows), as well as ill-defined enhancement in the intraconal space of the left orbit (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows mild proptosis of the left orbit (arrow). The patient underwent treatment with fractionated stereotactic radiation therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Vitreous amyloid deposition in a 65-year-old man with blurry vision. (a) Wide-angle color fundus photograph of the right eye obtained after a prior vitrectomy shows a clear and transparent central vitreous space, a normal macula (*), optic nerve (arrow), and peripheral laser photocoagulation scars (curved arrow). Note the small amount of residual peripheral vitreous opacities (residual amyloid; arrowheads). (b) Wide-field color fundus photograph of the left eye before vitrectomy shows vitreous opacities (amyloid deposits; arrowheads) that obscure the view of the optic nerve, retinal vessels, and macula. The amyloid material appears green (artificial color from the imaging system), as the true color is whitish yellow. Liquid chromatography–tandem mass spectrometry of vitreous specimen from the left eye confirmed a peptide profile consistent with a hereditary variant of ATTR (not shown). (Case courtesy of Timothy W. Olsen, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig4a.jpeg" height="1131" width="1336" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Vitreous amyloid deposition in a 65-year-old man with blurry vision. <b>(a)</b> Wide-angle color fundus photograph of the right eye obtained after a prior vitrectomy shows a clear and transparent central vitreous space, a normal macula (*), optic nerve (arrow), and peripheral laser photocoagulation scars (curved arrow). Note the small amount of residual peripheral vitreous opacities (residual amyloid; arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Wide-field color fundus photograph of the left eye before vitrectomy shows vitreous opacities (amyloid deposits; arrowheads) that obscure the view of the optic nerve, retinal vessels, and macula. The amyloid material appears green (artificial color from the imaging system), as the true color is whitish yellow. Liquid chromatography–tandem mass spectrometry of vitreous specimen from the left eye confirmed a peptide profile consistent with a hereditary variant of ATTR (not shown). (Case courtesy of Timothy W. Olsen, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Vitreous amyloid deposition in a 65-year-old man with blurry vision. (a) Wide-angle color fundus photograph of the right eye obtained after a prior vitrectomy shows a clear and transparent central vitreous space, a normal macula (*), optic nerve (arrow), and peripheral laser photocoagulation scars (curved arrow). Note the small amount of residual peripheral vitreous opacities (residual amyloid; arrowheads). (b) Wide-field color fundus photograph of the left eye before vitrectomy shows vitreous opacities (amyloid deposits; arrowheads) that obscure the view of the optic nerve, retinal vessels, and macula. The amyloid material appears green (artificial color from the imaging system), as the true color is whitish yellow. Liquid chromatography–tandem mass spectrometry of vitreous specimen from the left eye confirmed a peptide profile consistent with a hereditary variant of ATTR (not shown). (Case courtesy of Timothy W. Olsen, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig4b.jpeg" height="1131" width="1314" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Vitreous amyloid deposition in a 65-year-old man with blurry vision. <b>(a)</b> Wide-angle color fundus photograph of the right eye obtained after a prior vitrectomy shows a clear and transparent central vitreous space, a normal macula (*), optic nerve (arrow), and peripheral laser photocoagulation scars (curved arrow). Note the small amount of residual peripheral vitreous opacities (residual amyloid; arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Wide-field color fundus photograph of the left eye before vitrectomy shows vitreous opacities (amyloid deposits; arrowheads) that obscure the view of the optic nerve, retinal vessels, and macula. The amyloid material appears green (artificial color from the imaging system), as the true color is whitish yellow. Liquid chromatography–tandem mass spectrometry of vitreous specimen from the left eye confirmed a peptide profile consistent with a hereditary variant of ATTR (not shown). (Case courtesy of Timothy W. Olsen, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac interstitial amyloid (pericellular and nodular) and endocardial TTR mutant-type amyloid deposition in a 67-year-old man with nonischemic cardiomyopathy, confirmed following cardiac transplant. (a) Short-axis time of inversion scout MR image (left) of the heart shows myocardial nulling (arrowhead) before nulling of the blood pool (*). Short-axis gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (right) shows diffuse myocardial and subendocardial LGE (arrows). (b) Photograph shows short-axis slices of an explanted gross pathologic specimen of the native heart with marked thickening of the ventricular walls, disproportionately involving the interventricular septum (arrowheads), and a waxy appearance of the myocardial cut surface due to diffuse interstitial amyloid deposition. (c) Photomicrograph of a hematoxylin-eosin–stained specimen at high-power (×100) magnification shows two patterns of myocardial amyloid deposition: pericellular pattern (arrows) and nodular pattern (dashed outline)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig5a.jpeg" height="1379" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Cardiac interstitial amyloid (pericellular and nodular) and endocardial <i>TTR</i> mutant-type amyloid deposition in a 67-year-old man with nonischemic cardiomyopathy, confirmed following cardiac transplant. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis time of inversion scout MR image (left) of the heart shows myocardial nulling (arrowhead) before nulling of the blood pool (*). Short-axis gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (right) shows diffuse myocardial and subendocardial LGE (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows short-axis slices of an explanted gross pathologic specimen of the native heart with marked thickening of the ventricular walls, disproportionately involving the interventricular septum (arrowheads), and a waxy appearance of the myocardial cut surface due to diffuse interstitial amyloid deposition. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of a hematoxylin-eosin–stained specimen at high-power (×100) magnification shows two patterns of myocardial amyloid deposition: pericellular pattern (arrows) and nodular pattern (dashed outline).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac interstitial amyloid (pericellular and nodular) and endocardial TTR mutant-type amyloid deposition in a 67-year-old man with nonischemic cardiomyopathy, confirmed following cardiac transplant. (a) Short-axis time of inversion scout MR image (left) of the heart shows myocardial nulling (arrowhead) before nulling of the blood pool (*). Short-axis gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (right) shows diffuse myocardial and subendocardial LGE (arrows). (b) Photograph shows short-axis slices of an explanted gross pathologic specimen of the native heart with marked thickening of the ventricular walls, disproportionately involving the interventricular septum (arrowheads), and a waxy appearance of the myocardial cut surface due to diffuse interstitial amyloid deposition. (c) Photomicrograph of a hematoxylin-eosin–stained specimen at high-power (×100) magnification shows two patterns of myocardial amyloid deposition: pericellular pattern (arrows) and nodular pattern (dashed outline)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig5b.jpeg" height="1121" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Cardiac interstitial amyloid (pericellular and nodular) and endocardial <i>TTR</i> mutant-type amyloid deposition in a 67-year-old man with nonischemic cardiomyopathy, confirmed following cardiac transplant. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis time of inversion scout MR image (left) of the heart shows myocardial nulling (arrowhead) before nulling of the blood pool (*). Short-axis gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (right) shows diffuse myocardial and subendocardial LGE (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows short-axis slices of an explanted gross pathologic specimen of the native heart with marked thickening of the ventricular walls, disproportionately involving the interventricular septum (arrowheads), and a waxy appearance of the myocardial cut surface due to diffuse interstitial amyloid deposition. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of a hematoxylin-eosin–stained specimen at high-power (×100) magnification shows two patterns of myocardial amyloid deposition: pericellular pattern (arrows) and nodular pattern (dashed outline).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiac interstitial amyloid (pericellular and nodular) and endocardial TTR mutant-type amyloid deposition in a 67-year-old man with nonischemic cardiomyopathy, confirmed following cardiac transplant. (a) Short-axis time of inversion scout MR image (left) of the heart shows myocardial nulling (arrowhead) before nulling of the blood pool (*). Short-axis gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (right) shows diffuse myocardial and subendocardial LGE (arrows). (b) Photograph shows short-axis slices of an explanted gross pathologic specimen of the native heart with marked thickening of the ventricular walls, disproportionately involving the interventricular septum (arrowheads), and a waxy appearance of the myocardial cut surface due to diffuse interstitial amyloid deposition. (c) Photomicrograph of a hematoxylin-eosin–stained specimen at high-power (×100) magnification shows two patterns of myocardial amyloid deposition: pericellular pattern (arrows) and nodular pattern (dashed outline)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig5c.jpeg" height="1164" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Cardiac interstitial amyloid (pericellular and nodular) and endocardial <i>TTR</i> mutant-type amyloid deposition in a 67-year-old man with nonischemic cardiomyopathy, confirmed following cardiac transplant. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis time of inversion scout MR image (left) of the heart shows myocardial nulling (arrowhead) before nulling of the blood pool (*). Short-axis gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image (right) shows diffuse myocardial and subendocardial LGE (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows short-axis slices of an explanted gross pathologic specimen of the native heart with marked thickening of the ventricular walls, disproportionately involving the interventricular septum (arrowheads), and a waxy appearance of the myocardial cut surface due to diffuse interstitial amyloid deposition. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph of a hematoxylin-eosin–stained specimen at high-power (×100) magnification shows two patterns of myocardial amyloid deposition: pericellular pattern (arrows) and nodular pattern (dashed outline).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="Tracheobronchial amyloidosis in two patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest (left) shows asymmetric thickening of the left tracheal wall (black arrow) in a 66-year-old woman with tracheal amyloidosis. Corresponding endoscopic image (right) shows a focal submucosal mass (red arrow), which was biopsied and proved to be nodular κ AL amyloidosis. (b) Coronal noncontrast CT image shows nodular irregular wall thickening and bulky calcifications in the tracheobronchial tree (arrows) in a 34-year-old man with tracheobronchial amyloidosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig6a.jpeg" height="1221" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Tracheobronchial amyloidosis in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest (left) shows asymmetric thickening of the left tracheal wall (black arrow) in a 66-year-old woman with tracheal amyloidosis. Corresponding endoscopic image (right) shows a focal submucosal mass (red arrow), which was biopsied and proved to be nodular κ AL amyloidosis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal noncontrast CT image shows nodular irregular wall thickening and bulky calcifications in the tracheobronchial tree (arrows) in a 34-year-old man with tracheobronchial amyloidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="Tracheobronchial amyloidosis in two patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest (left) shows asymmetric thickening of the left tracheal wall (black arrow) in a 66-year-old woman with tracheal amyloidosis. Corresponding endoscopic image (right) shows a focal submucosal mass (red arrow), which was biopsied and proved to be nodular κ AL amyloidosis. (b) Coronal noncontrast CT image shows nodular irregular wall thickening and bulky calcifications in the tracheobronchial tree (arrows) in a 34-year-old man with tracheobronchial amyloidosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig6b.jpeg" height="1618" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Tracheobronchial amyloidosis in two patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image of the chest (left) shows asymmetric thickening of the left tracheal wall (black arrow) in a 66-year-old woman with tracheal amyloidosis. Corresponding endoscopic image (right) shows a focal submucosal mass (red arrow), which was biopsied and proved to be nodular κ AL amyloidosis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal noncontrast CT image shows nodular irregular wall thickening and bulky calcifications in the tracheobronchial tree (arrows) in a 34-year-old man with tracheobronchial amyloidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Nodular parenchymal pulmonary amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AD. (a) Frontal chest radiograph shows right suprahilar and left mid- to upper-lung masslike opacities (arrows). (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT maximum intensity projection (MIP) image shows corresponding partially calcified subpleural soft-tissue masses (arrows). (c, d) Intraprocedural axial noncontrast CT image (c) shows percutaneous CT-guided biopsy of the left upper lobe mass (arrow in c), which stained positive with Congo red at microscopy, consistent with the presence of amyloid. The mass had enlarged (arrow in d) on the follow-up contrast-enhanced CT image (d) of the chest obtained 4 years later."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig7a.jpeg" height="1706" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Nodular parenchymal pulmonary amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AD. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows right suprahilar and left mid- to upper-lung masslike opacities (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT maximum intensity projection (MIP) image shows corresponding partially calcified subpleural soft-tissue masses (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Intraprocedural axial noncontrast CT image <b>(c)</b> shows percutaneous CT-guided biopsy of the left upper lobe mass (arrow in <b>c</b>), which stained positive with Congo red at microscopy, consistent with the presence of amyloid. The mass had enlarged (arrow in <b>d</b>) on the follow-up contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(d)</b> of the chest obtained 4 years later.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="Nodular parenchymal pulmonary amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AD. (a) Frontal chest radiograph shows right suprahilar and left mid- to upper-lung masslike opacities (arrows). (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT maximum intensity projection (MIP) image shows corresponding partially calcified subpleural soft-tissue masses (arrows). (c, d) Intraprocedural axial noncontrast CT image (c) shows percutaneous CT-guided biopsy of the left upper lobe mass (arrow in c), which stained positive with Congo red at microscopy, consistent with the presence of amyloid. The mass had enlarged (arrow in d) on the follow-up contrast-enhanced CT image (d) of the chest obtained 4 years later."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig7b.jpeg" height="1706" width="1562" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Nodular parenchymal pulmonary amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AD. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows right suprahilar and left mid- to upper-lung masslike opacities (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT maximum intensity projection (MIP) image shows corresponding partially calcified subpleural soft-tissue masses (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Intraprocedural axial noncontrast CT image <b>(c)</b> shows percutaneous CT-guided biopsy of the left upper lobe mass (arrow in <b>c</b>), which stained positive with Congo red at microscopy, consistent with the presence of amyloid. The mass had enlarged (arrow in <b>d</b>) on the follow-up contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(d)</b> of the chest obtained 4 years later.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic" aria-label="Nodular parenchymal pulmonary amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AD. (a) Frontal chest radiograph shows right suprahilar and left mid- to upper-lung masslike opacities (arrows). (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT maximum intensity projection (MIP) image shows corresponding partially calcified subpleural soft-tissue masses (arrows). (c, d) Intraprocedural axial noncontrast CT image (c) shows percutaneous CT-guided biopsy of the left upper lobe mass (arrow in c), which stained positive with Congo red at microscopy, consistent with the presence of amyloid. The mass had enlarged (arrow in d) on the follow-up contrast-enhanced CT image (d) of the chest obtained 4 years later."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig7c.jpeg" height="1440" width="1021" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Nodular parenchymal pulmonary amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AD. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows right suprahilar and left mid- to upper-lung masslike opacities (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT maximum intensity projection (MIP) image shows corresponding partially calcified subpleural soft-tissue masses (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Intraprocedural axial noncontrast CT image <b>(c)</b> shows percutaneous CT-guided biopsy of the left upper lobe mass (arrow in <b>c</b>), which stained positive with Congo red at microscopy, consistent with the presence of amyloid. The mass had enlarged (arrow in <b>d</b>) on the follow-up contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(d)</b> of the chest obtained 4 years later.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic" aria-label="Nodular parenchymal pulmonary amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AD. (a) Frontal chest radiograph shows right suprahilar and left mid- to upper-lung masslike opacities (arrows). (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT maximum intensity projection (MIP) image shows corresponding partially calcified subpleural soft-tissue masses (arrows). (c, d) Intraprocedural axial noncontrast CT image (c) shows percutaneous CT-guided biopsy of the left upper lobe mass (arrow in c), which stained positive with Congo red at microscopy, consistent with the presence of amyloid. The mass had enlarged (arrow in d) on the follow-up contrast-enhanced CT image (d) of the chest obtained 4 years later."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig7d.jpeg" height="1440" width="1028" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Nodular parenchymal pulmonary amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AD. <b>(a)</b> Frontal chest radiograph shows right suprahilar and left mid- to upper-lung masslike opacities (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT maximum intensity projection (MIP) image shows corresponding partially calcified subpleural soft-tissue masses (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Intraprocedural axial noncontrast CT image <b>(c)</b> shows percutaneous CT-guided biopsy of the left upper lobe mass (arrow in <b>c</b>), which stained positive with Congo red at microscopy, consistent with the presence of amyloid. The mass had enlarged (arrow in <b>d</b>) on the follow-up contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(d)</b> of the chest obtained 4 years later.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of pulmonary amyloidosis in three patients. (a) Axial noncontrast MIP CT image shows nodular areas of consolidation (arrows) in a 77-year-old woman with nodular parenchymal type AL amyloidosis and plasma cell myeloma. (b) Axial prone noncontrast CT image shows basilar and peripheral-predominant confluent consolidation (arrows) and interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead) in a 73-year-old woman with diffuse alveolar septal AL amyloidosis. (c) Axial supine noncontrast CT image shows 2–4-mm micronodules and calcifications in the right lower lobe (dashed circle), interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead), bilateral pleural effusions (*), and right middle lobe collapse (arrow), consistent with a diffuse alveolar septal pattern of disease in a 66-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, confirmed by lung wedge biopsy results."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig8a.jpeg" height="1136" width="1581" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Patterns of pulmonary amyloidosis in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial noncontrast MIP CT image shows nodular areas of consolidation (arrows) in a 77-year-old woman with nodular parenchymal type AL amyloidosis and plasma cell myeloma. <b>(b)</b> Axial prone noncontrast CT image shows basilar and peripheral-predominant confluent consolidation (arrows) and interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead) in a 73-year-old woman with diffuse alveolar septal AL amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial supine noncontrast CT image shows 2–4-mm micronodules and calcifications in the right lower lobe (dashed circle), interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead), bilateral pleural effusions (*), and right middle lobe collapse (arrow), consistent with a diffuse alveolar septal pattern of disease in a 66-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, confirmed by lung wedge biopsy results.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of pulmonary amyloidosis in three patients. (a) Axial noncontrast MIP CT image shows nodular areas of consolidation (arrows) in a 77-year-old woman with nodular parenchymal type AL amyloidosis and plasma cell myeloma. (b) Axial prone noncontrast CT image shows basilar and peripheral-predominant confluent consolidation (arrows) and interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead) in a 73-year-old woman with diffuse alveolar septal AL amyloidosis. (c) Axial supine noncontrast CT image shows 2–4-mm micronodules and calcifications in the right lower lobe (dashed circle), interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead), bilateral pleural effusions (*), and right middle lobe collapse (arrow), consistent with a diffuse alveolar septal pattern of disease in a 66-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, confirmed by lung wedge biopsy results."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig8b.jpeg" height="1140" width="1570" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Patterns of pulmonary amyloidosis in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial noncontrast MIP CT image shows nodular areas of consolidation (arrows) in a 77-year-old woman with nodular parenchymal type AL amyloidosis and plasma cell myeloma. <b>(b)</b> Axial prone noncontrast CT image shows basilar and peripheral-predominant confluent consolidation (arrows) and interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead) in a 73-year-old woman with diffuse alveolar septal AL amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial supine noncontrast CT image shows 2–4-mm micronodules and calcifications in the right lower lobe (dashed circle), interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead), bilateral pleural effusions (*), and right middle lobe collapse (arrow), consistent with a diffuse alveolar septal pattern of disease in a 66-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, confirmed by lung wedge biopsy results.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of pulmonary amyloidosis in three patients. (a) Axial noncontrast MIP CT image shows nodular areas of consolidation (arrows) in a 77-year-old woman with nodular parenchymal type AL amyloidosis and plasma cell myeloma. (b) Axial prone noncontrast CT image shows basilar and peripheral-predominant confluent consolidation (arrows) and interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead) in a 73-year-old woman with diffuse alveolar septal AL amyloidosis. (c) Axial supine noncontrast CT image shows 2–4-mm micronodules and calcifications in the right lower lobe (dashed circle), interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead), bilateral pleural effusions (*), and right middle lobe collapse (arrow), consistent with a diffuse alveolar septal pattern of disease in a 66-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, confirmed by lung wedge biopsy results."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig8c.jpeg" height="1388" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Patterns of pulmonary amyloidosis in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial noncontrast MIP CT image shows nodular areas of consolidation (arrows) in a 77-year-old woman with nodular parenchymal type AL amyloidosis and plasma cell myeloma. <b>(b)</b> Axial prone noncontrast CT image shows basilar and peripheral-predominant confluent consolidation (arrows) and interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead) in a 73-year-old woman with diffuse alveolar septal AL amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial supine noncontrast CT image shows 2–4-mm micronodules and calcifications in the right lower lobe (dashed circle), interlobular septal thickening (arrowhead), bilateral pleural effusions (*), and right middle lobe collapse (arrow), consistent with a diffuse alveolar septal pattern of disease in a 66-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, confirmed by lung wedge biopsy results.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Renal amyloidosis and a mimic (medullary nephrocalcinosis) in three patients. (a) Axial noncontrast CT image shows amorphous parenchymal calcifications in the right kidney (arrow) in a 71-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Mild caliectasis is present. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows thick curvilinear mural calcifications in the renal pelvis (arrow) in a patient with localized amyloidosis. (c) Axial noncontrast CT image shows a medullary pattern of calcifications (arrows) and a renal stone (arrowhead) in a 43-year-old woman with medullary nephrocalcinosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig9a.jpeg" height="1188" width="1135" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Renal amyloidosis and a mimic (medullary nephrocalcinosis) in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows amorphous parenchymal calcifications in the right kidney (arrow) in a 71-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Mild caliectasis is present. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows thick curvilinear mural calcifications in the renal pelvis (arrow) in a patient with localized amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows a medullary pattern of calcifications (arrows) and a renal stone (arrowhead) in a 43-year-old woman with medullary nephrocalcinosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="Renal amyloidosis and a mimic (medullary nephrocalcinosis) in three patients. (a) Axial noncontrast CT image shows amorphous parenchymal calcifications in the right kidney (arrow) in a 71-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Mild caliectasis is present. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows thick curvilinear mural calcifications in the renal pelvis (arrow) in a patient with localized amyloidosis. (c) Axial noncontrast CT image shows a medullary pattern of calcifications (arrows) and a renal stone (arrowhead) in a 43-year-old woman with medullary nephrocalcinosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig9b.jpeg" height="1188" width="1135" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Renal amyloidosis and a mimic (medullary nephrocalcinosis) in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows amorphous parenchymal calcifications in the right kidney (arrow) in a 71-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Mild caliectasis is present. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows thick curvilinear mural calcifications in the renal pelvis (arrow) in a patient with localized amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows a medullary pattern of calcifications (arrows) and a renal stone (arrowhead) in a 43-year-old woman with medullary nephrocalcinosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic" aria-label="Renal amyloidosis and a mimic (medullary nephrocalcinosis) in three patients. (a) Axial noncontrast CT image shows amorphous parenchymal calcifications in the right kidney (arrow) in a 71-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Mild caliectasis is present. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows thick curvilinear mural calcifications in the renal pelvis (arrow) in a patient with localized amyloidosis. (c) Axial noncontrast CT image shows a medullary pattern of calcifications (arrows) and a renal stone (arrowhead) in a 43-year-old woman with medullary nephrocalcinosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig9c.jpeg" height="1188" width="1030" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Renal amyloidosis and a mimic (medullary nephrocalcinosis) in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows amorphous parenchymal calcifications in the right kidney (arrow) in a 71-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. Mild caliectasis is present. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows thick curvilinear mural calcifications in the renal pelvis (arrow) in a patient with localized amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows a medullary pattern of calcifications (arrows) and a renal stone (arrowhead) in a 43-year-old woman with medullary nephrocalcinosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Bladder amyloidosis in three patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows asymmetric irregular wall thickening of the left lateral and posterior bladder wall (arrow) in a 75-year-old man with painless gross hematuria who was diagnosed with ATTR localized to the bladder. The findings were initially suspicious for neoplasm at CT. The lesion extends to the left ureterovesical junction without left ureteral dilatation. (b) Axial noncontrast CT image shows curvilinear calcification of the bladder wall (arrow); high-attenuation urine within the bladder, indicative of acute bladder clot (*); and a diffuse increase in perivesical and perirectal soft-tissue attenuation (arrowheads) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. (c) Axial noncontrast CT image (left) shows subtle mural calcifications at the right trigone of the bladder (white arrow) in a 49-year-old man with normal bone marrow biopsy results and biopsy-proven localized AL amyloidosis, involving the bladder. Corresponding image obtained at cystoscopy (right) shows punctate foci of calcification (black arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig10a.jpeg" height="1306" width="1379" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Bladder amyloidosis in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows asymmetric irregular wall thickening of the left lateral and posterior bladder wall (arrow) in a 75-year-old man with painless gross hematuria who was diagnosed with ATTR localized to the 