ar-old man with normal bone marrow biopsy results and biopsy-proven localized AL amyloidosis, involving the bladder. Corresponding image obtained at cystoscopy (right) shows punctate foci of calcification (black arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig10b.jpeg" height="1306" width="1371" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Bladder amyloidosis in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows asymmetric irregular wall thickening of the left lateral and posterior bladder wall (arrow) in a 75-year-old man with painless gross hematuria who was diagnosed with ATTR localized to the bladder. The findings were initially suspicious for neoplasm at CT. The lesion extends to the left ureterovesical junction without left ureteral dilatation. <b>(b)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows curvilinear calcification of the bladder wall (arrow); high-attenuation urine within the bladder, indicative of acute bladder clot (*); and a diffuse increase in perivesical and perirectal soft-tissue attenuation (arrowheads) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image (left) shows subtle mural calcifications at the right trigone of the bladder (white arrow) in a 49-year-old man with normal bone marrow biopsy results and biopsy-proven localized AL amyloidosis, involving the bladder. Corresponding image obtained at cystoscopy (right) shows punctate foci of calcification (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic" aria-label="Bladder amyloidosis in three patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows asymmetric irregular wall thickening of the left lateral and posterior bladder wall (arrow) in a 75-year-old man with painless gross hematuria who was diagnosed with ATTR localized to the bladder. The findings were initially suspicious for neoplasm at CT. The lesion extends to the left ureterovesical junction without left ureteral dilatation. (b) Axial noncontrast CT image shows curvilinear calcification of the bladder wall (arrow); high-attenuation urine within the bladder, indicative of acute bladder clot (*); and a diffuse increase in perivesical and perirectal soft-tissue attenuation (arrowheads) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. (c) Axial noncontrast CT image (left) shows subtle mural calcifications at the right trigone of the bladder (white arrow) in a 49-year-old man with normal bone marrow biopsy results and biopsy-proven localized AL amyloidosis, involving the bladder. Corresponding image obtained at cystoscopy (right) shows punctate foci of calcification (black arrow)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig10c.jpeg" height="1040" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Bladder amyloidosis in three patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows asymmetric irregular wall thickening of the left lateral and posterior bladder wall (arrow) in a 75-year-old man with painless gross hematuria who was diagnosed with ATTR localized to the bladder. The findings were initially suspicious for neoplasm at CT. The lesion extends to the left ureterovesical junction without left ureteral dilatation. <b>(b)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image shows curvilinear calcification of the bladder wall (arrow); high-attenuation urine within the bladder, indicative of acute bladder clot (*); and a diffuse increase in perivesical and perirectal soft-tissue attenuation (arrowheads) in a 73-year-old man with systemic amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image (left) shows subtle mural calcifications at the right trigone of the bladder (white arrow) in a 49-year-old man with normal bone marrow biopsy results and biopsy-proven localized AL amyloidosis, involving the bladder. Corresponding image obtained at cystoscopy (right) shows punctate foci of calcification (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of hepatic amyloid deposition in different patients with hepatomegaly. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled appearance of the liver (arrows) in a 72-year-old woman with hepatic AL amyloidosis. (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled nutmeg appearance of the hepatic parenchyma in a 50-year-old woman with AA amyloidosis. (c) Coronal contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows calcifications (arrow) at the dome of the liver in a 73-year-old man with κ AL amyloidosis. (d) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the portal venous phase shows heterogeneous hypoattenuation of the right hepatic lobe, mimicking steatosis, in a 74-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. (e) Photographs of the anterior and posterior views of the gross pathologic specimen of an explanted liver following simultaneous kidney-liver transplant for amyloid-related disease in a 64-year-old man with AA amyloidosis show a dark brown color of the hepatica parenchyma due to diffuse iron deposition (hemosiderosis). (f) Photomicrograph of the liver biopsy specimen shows a sinusoidal pattern of disease with diffuse amyloid deposition (pale pink material, arrows) along the hepatic sinusoids. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig11a.jpeg" height="1307" width="1157" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Patterns of hepatic amyloid deposition in different patients with hepatomegaly. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled appearance of the liver (arrows) in a 72-year-old woman with hepatic AL amyloidosis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled nutmeg appearance of the hepatic parenchyma in a 50-year-old woman with AA amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows calcifications (arrow) at the dome of the liver in a 73-year-old man with κ AL amyloidosis. <b>(d)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the portal venous phase shows heterogeneous hypoattenuation of the right hepatic lobe, mimicking steatosis, in a 74-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Photographs of the anterior and posterior views of the gross pathologic specimen of an explanted liver following simultaneous kidney-liver transplant for amyloid-related disease in a 64-year-old man with AA amyloidosis show a dark brown color of the hepatica parenchyma due to diffuse iron deposition (hemosiderosis). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph of the liver biopsy specimen shows a sinusoidal pattern of disease with diffuse amyloid deposition (pale pink material, arrows) along the hepatic sinusoids. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of hepatic amyloid deposition in different patients with hepatomegaly. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled appearance of the liver (arrows) in a 72-year-old woman with hepatic AL amyloidosis. (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled nutmeg appearance of the hepatic parenchyma in a 50-year-old woman with AA amyloidosis. (c) Coronal c