an with AL amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Photographs of the anterior and posterior views of the gross pathologic specimen of an explanted liver following simultaneous kidney-liver transplant for amyloid-related disease in a 64-year-old man with AA amyloidosis show a dark brown color of the hepatica parenchyma due to diffuse iron deposition (hemosiderosis). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph of the liver biopsy specimen shows a sinusoidal pattern of disease with diffuse amyloid deposition (pale pink material, arrows) along the hepatic sinusoids. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11e" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of hepatic amyloid deposition in different patients with hepatomegaly. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled appearance of the liver (arrows) in a 72-year-old woman with hepatic AL amyloidosis. (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled nutmeg appearance of the hepatic parenchyma in a 50-year-old woman with AA amyloidosis. (c) Coronal contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows calcifications (arrow) at the dome of the liver in a 73-year-old man with κ AL amyloidosis. (d) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the portal venous phase shows heterogeneous hypoattenuation of the right hepatic lobe, mimicking steatosis, in a 74-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. (e) Photographs of the anterior and posterior views of the gross pathologic specimen of an explanted liver following simultaneous kidney-liver transplant for amyloid-related disease in a 64-year-old man with AA amyloidosis show a dark brown color of the hepatica parenchyma due to diffuse iron deposition (hemosiderosis). (f) Photomicrograph of the liver biopsy specimen shows a sinusoidal pattern of disease with diffuse amyloid deposition (pale pink material, arrows) along the hepatic sinusoids. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig11e.jpeg" height="1182" width="2553" aria-labelledby="fig11e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11e</span>. Patterns of hepatic amyloid deposition in different patients with hepatomegaly. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled appearance of the liver (arrows) in a 72-year-old woman with hepatic AL amyloidosis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled nutmeg appearance of the hepatic parenchyma in a 50-year-old woman with AA amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows calcifications (arrow) at the dome of the liver in a 73-year-old man with κ AL amyloidosis. <b>(d)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the portal venous phase shows heterogeneous hypoattenuation of the right hepatic lobe, mimicking steatosis, in a 74-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Photographs of the anterior and posterior views of the gross pathologic specimen of an explanted liver following simultaneous kidney-liver transplant for amyloid-related disease in a 64-year-old man with AA amyloidosis show a dark brown color of the hepatica parenchyma due to diffuse iron deposition (hemosiderosis). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph of the liver biopsy specimen shows a sinusoidal pattern of disease with diffuse amyloid deposition (pale pink material, arrows) along the hepatic sinusoids. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig11e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11f" class="graphic" aria-label="Patterns of hepatic amyloid deposition in different patients with hepatomegaly. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled appearance of the liver (arrows) in a 72-year-old woman with hepatic AL amyloidosis. (b) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled nutmeg appearance of the hepatic parenchyma in a 50-year-old woman with AA amyloidosis. (c) Coronal contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows calcifications (arrow) at the dome of the liver in a 73-year-old man with κ AL amyloidosis. (d) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the portal venous phase shows heterogeneous hypoattenuation of the right hepatic lobe, mimicking steatosis, in a 74-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. (e) Photographs of the anterior and posterior views of the gross pathologic specimen of an explanted liver following simultaneous kidney-liver transplant for amyloid-related disease in a 64-year-old man with AA amyloidosis show a dark brown color of the hepatica parenchyma due to diffuse iron deposition (hemosiderosis). (f) Photomicrograph of the liver biopsy specimen shows a sinusoidal pattern of disease with diffuse amyloid deposition (pale pink material, arrows) along the hepatic sinusoids. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig11f.jpeg" height="1033" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig11f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11f</span>. Patterns of hepatic amyloid deposition in different patients with hepatomegaly. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled appearance of the liver (arrows) in a 72-year-old woman with hepatic AL amyloidosis. <b>(b)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a mottled nutmeg appearance of the hepatic parenchyma in a 50-year-old woman with AA amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced arterial phase CT image shows calcifications (arrow) at the dome of the liver in a 73-year-old man with κ AL amyloidosis. <b>(d)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in the portal venous phase shows heterogeneous hypoattenuation of the right hepatic lobe, mimicking steatosis, in a 74-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. <b>(e)</b> Photographs of the anterior and posterior views of the gross pathologic specimen of an explanted liver following simultaneous kidney-liver transplant for amyloid-related disease in a 64-year-old man with AA amyloidosis show a dark brown color of the hepatica parenchyma due to diffuse iron deposition (hemosiderosis). <b>(f)</b> Photomicrograph of the liver biopsy specimen shows a sinusoidal pattern of disease with diffuse amyloid deposition (pale pink material, arrows) along the hepatic sinusoids. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×200.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig11f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="Hepatic amyloidosis and increased liver stiffness in a 54-year-old woman with λ type AL amyloidosis. The patient had elevated alkaline phosphatase levels three times the normal amount at 330 IU/L. (a) MR elastography stiffness color map with a scale of 0–8 kPa shows markedly increased stiffness (mean, 6.5 kPa; range, 6.0–7.3 kPa). The normal value for the liver is less than 2.9 kPa. (b) Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image obtained at the corresponding level shows no apparent cirrhotic configuration of the liver or hepatomegaly. Mild splenomegaly is present. The results of a US-guided liver biopsy confirmed sinusoidal and portal amyloid deposits, confirmed with the use of Congo red stain."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig12a.jpeg" height="1355" width="1376" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Hepatic amyloidosis and increased liver stiffness in a 54-year-old woman with λ type AL amyloidosis. The patient had elevated alkaline phosphatase levels three times the normal amount at 330 IU/L. <b>(a)</b> MR elastography stiffness color map with a scale of 0–8 kPa shows markedly increased stiffness (mean, 6.5 kPa; range, 6.0–7.3 kPa). The normal value for the liver is less than 2.9 kPa. <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image obtained at the corresponding level shows no apparent cirrhotic configuration of the liver or hepatomegaly. Mild splenomegaly is present. The results of a US-guided liver biopsy confirmed sinusoidal and portal amyloid deposits, confirmed with the use of Congo red stain.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic" aria-label="Hepatic amyloidosis and increased liver stiffness in a 54-year-old woman with λ type AL amyloidosis. The patient had elevated alkaline phosphatase levels three times the normal amount at 330 IU/L. (a) MR elastography stiffness color map with a scale of 0–8 kPa shows markedly increased stiffness (mean, 6.5 kPa; range, 6.0–7.3 kPa). The normal value for the liver is less than 2.9 kPa. (b) Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image obtained at the corresponding level shows no apparent cirrhotic configuration of the liver or hepatomegaly. Mild splenomegaly is present. The results of a US-guided liver biopsy confirmed sinusoidal and portal amyloid deposits, confirmed with the use of Congo red stain."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig12b.jpeg" height="1355" width="1372" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Hepatic amyloidosis and increased liver stiffness in a 54-year-old woman with λ type AL amyloidosis. The patient had elevated alkaline phosphatase levels three times the normal amount at 330 IU/L. <b>(a)</b> MR elastography stiffness color map with a scale of 0–8 kPa shows markedly increased stiffness (mean, 6.5 kPa; range, 6.0–7.3 kPa). The normal value for the liver is less than 2.9 kPa. <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image obtained at the corresponding level shows no apparent cirrhotic configuration of the liver or hepatomegaly. Mild splenomegaly is present. The results of a US-guided liver biopsy confirmed sinusoidal and portal amyloid deposits, confirmed with the use of Congo red stain.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="Splenic involvement by secondary amyloidosis in a 40-year-old man with mesenteric Castleman disease. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a 5-cm soft-tissue mass (arrow) within the jejunal mesentery containing coarse calcification and splenomegaly (arrowheads) measuring up to 23 cm in the craniocaudal dimension. (b) Coronal FDG PET/CT fusion image shows the mesenteric mass (arrow) to be hypermetabolic, with a maximum standardized uptake value of 9.1, and splenomegaly without associated hypermetabolic activity (arrowheads). The results of a CT-guided percutaneous needle biopsy of the mesenteric mass confirmed AA-type amyloid deposition. Surgical resection of the mesenteric mass and splenectomy were performed to rule out malignancy. Surgical pathologic analysis results confirmed that the mesenteric mass was Castleman disease, plasma cell type, associated with AA-type amyloid deposition in the spleen and mesenteric mass. No malignant cells were identified."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig13a.jpeg" height="1579" width="1445" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Splenic involvement by secondary amyloidosis in a 40-year-old man with mesenteric Castleman disease. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a 5-cm soft-tissue mass (arrow) within the jejunal mesentery containing coarse calcification and splenomegaly (arrowheads) measuring up to 23 cm in the craniocaudal dimension. <b>(b)</b> Coronal FDG PET/CT fusion image shows the mesenteric mass (arrow) to be hypermetabolic, with a maximum standardized uptake value of 9.1, and splenomegaly without associated hypermetabolic activity (arrowheads). The results of a CT-guided percutaneous needle biopsy of the mesenteric mass confirmed AA-type amyloid deposition. Surgical resection of the mesenteric mass and splenectomy were performed to rule out malignancy. Surgical pathologic analysis results confirmed that the mesenteric mass was Castleman disease, plasma cell type, associated with AA-type amyloid deposition in the spleen and mesenteric mass. No malignant cells were identified.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic" aria-label="Splenic involvement by secondary amyloidosis in a 40-year-old man with mesenteric Castleman disease. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a 5-cm soft-tissue mass (arrow) within the jejunal mesentery containing coarse calcification and splenomegaly (arrowheads) measuring up to 23 cm in the craniocaudal dimension. (b) Coronal FDG PET/CT fusion image shows the mesenteric mass (arrow) to be hypermetabolic, with a maximum standardized uptake value of 9.1, and splenomegaly without associated hypermetabolic activity (arrowheads). The results of a CT-guided percutaneous needle biopsy of the mesenteric mass confirmed AA-type amyloid deposition. Surgical resection of the mesenteric mass and splenectomy were performed to rule out malignancy. Surgical pathologic analysis results confirmed that the mesenteric mass was Castleman disease, plasma cell type, associated with AA-type amyloid deposition in the spleen and mesenteric mass. No malignant cells were identified."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig13b.jpeg" height="1579" width="1305" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Splenic involvement by secondary amyloidosis in a 40-year-old man with mesenteric Castleman disease. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a 5-cm soft-tissue mass (arrow) within the jejunal mesentery containing coarse calcification and splenomegaly (arrowheads) measuring up to 23 cm in the craniocaudal dimension. <b>(b)</b> Coronal FDG PET/CT fusion image shows the mesenteric mass (arrow) to be hypermetabolic, with a maximum standardized uptake value of 9.1, and splenomegaly without associated hypermetabolic activity (arrowheads). The results of a CT-guided percutaneous needle biopsy of the mesenteric mass confirmed AA-type amyloid deposition. Surgical resection of the mesenteric mass and splenectomy were performed to rule out malignancy. Surgical pathologic analysis results confirmed that the mesenteric mass was Castleman disease, plasma cell type, associated with AA-type amyloid deposition in the spleen and mesenteric mass. No malignant cells were identified.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel amyloidosis in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the small bowel loops (arrows). (b) Endoscopic image of the duodenum shows a focal mucosal ulceration (arrow). (c) Photomicrographs of a duodenal biopsy specimen shows pale pink amorphous material (arrows) occupying the lamina propria (left), which stains positive with Congo red stain (right), consistent with the presence of amyloid. (Hematoxylin-eosin and Congo red stains, respectively; original magnification, ×100)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig14a.jpeg" height="1751" width="1512" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Small bowel amyloidosis in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the small bowel loops (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image of the duodenum shows a focal mucosal ulceration (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Photomicrographs of a duodenal biopsy specimen shows pale pink amorphous material (arrows) occupying the lamina propria (left), which stains positive with Congo red stain (right), consistent with the presence of amyloid. (Hematoxylin-eosin and Congo red stains, respectively; original magnification, ×100).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel amyloidosis in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the small bowel loops (arrows). (b) Endoscopic image of the duodenum shows a focal mucosal ulceration (arrow). (c) Photomicrographs of a duodenal biopsy specimen shows pale pink amorphous material (arrows) occupying the lamina propria (left), which stains positive with Congo red stain (right), consistent with the presence of amyloid. (Hematoxylin-eosin and Congo red stains, respectively; original magnification, ×100)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig14b.jpeg" height="1389" width="1134" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Small bowel amyloidosis in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the small bowel loops (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image of the duodenum shows a focal mucosal ulceration (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Photomicrographs of a duodenal biopsy specimen shows pale pink amorphous material (arrows) occupying the lamina propria (left), which stains positive with Congo red stain (right), consistent with the presence of amyloid. (Hematoxylin-eosin and Congo red stains, respectively; original magnification, ×100).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic" aria-label="Small bowel amyloidosis in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma. (a) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the small bowel loops (arrows). (b) Endoscopic image of the duodenum shows a focal mucosal ulceration (arrow). (c) Photomicrographs of a duodenal biopsy specimen shows pale pink amorphous material (arrows) occupying the lamina propria (left), which stains positive with Congo red stain (right), consistent with the presence of amyloid. (Hematoxylin-eosin and Congo red stains, respectively; original magnification, ×100)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig14c.jpeg" height="803" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Small bowel amyloidosis in a 71-year-old woman with multiple myeloma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image shows diffuse wall thickening of the small bowel loops (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image of the duodenum shows a focal mucosal ulceration (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Photomicrographs of a duodenal biopsy specimen shows pale pink amorphous material (arrows) occupying the lamina propria (left), which stains positive with Congo red stain (right), consistent with the presence of amyloid. (Hematoxylin-eosin and Congo red stains, respectively; original magnification, ×100).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Manifestations of peritoneal and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in four patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows infiltrative soft-tissue and dystrophic calcifications (arrows) in the omentum and mesentery in a 70-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, initially thought to represent peritoneal carcinomatosis. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue infiltration and thickening centered in the bilateral pelvic sidewall and presacral regions of the rectosigmoid mesentery with associated calcifications (arrows) in a 68-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. (c) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images show soft-tissue infiltration of the mesenteric fat (arrowheads), as well as involvement of the renal fascia and lymphatics, which are highlighted and thickened (arrows) in an 81-year-old man with amyloidosis. (d) Coronal (top) and axial (bottom) contrast-enhanced CT images show infiltrative soft tissue in the retroperitoneum encasing the aorta (arrows) and associated with calcifications (arrowheads) in a 73-year-old man with amyloidosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig15a.jpeg" height="988" width="1255" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Manifestations of peritoneal and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows infiltrative soft-tissue and dystrophic calcifications (arrows) in the omentum and mesentery in a 70-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, initially thought to represent peritoneal carcinomatosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue infiltration and thickening centered in the bilateral pelvic sidewall and presacral regions of the rectosigmoid mesentery with associated calcifications (arrows) in a 68-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images show soft-tissue infiltration of the mesenteric fat (arrowheads), as well as involvement of the renal fascia and lymphatics, which are highlighted and thickened (arrows) in an 81-year-old man with amyloidosis. <b>(d)</b> Coronal (top) and axial (bottom) contrast-enhanced CT images show infiltrative soft tissue in the retroperitoneum encasing the aorta (arrows) and associated with calcifications (arrowheads) in a 73-year-old man with amyloidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic" aria-label="Manifestations of peritoneal and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in four patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows infiltrative soft-tissue and dystrophic calcifications (arrows) in the omentum and mesentery in a 70-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, initially thought to represent peritoneal carcinomatosis. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue infiltration and thickening centered in the bilateral pelvic sidewall and presacral regions of the rectosigmoid mesentery with associated calcifications (arrows) in a 68-year-old man w