oft-tissue infiltration of the mesenteric fat (arrowheads), as well as involvement of the renal fascia and lymphatics, which are highlighted and thickened (arrows) in an 81-year-old man with amyloidosis. <b>(d)</b> Coronal (top) and axial (bottom) contrast-enhanced CT images show infiltrative soft tissue in the retroperitoneum encasing the aorta (arrows) and associated with calcifications (arrowheads) in a 73-year-old man with amyloidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic" aria-label="Manifestations of peritoneal and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in four patients. (a) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows infiltrative soft-tissue and dystrophic calcifications (arrows) in the omentum and mesentery in a 70-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, initially thought to represent peritoneal carcinomatosis. (b) Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue infiltration and thickening centered in the bilateral pelvic sidewall and presacral regions of the rectosigmoid mesentery with associated calcifications (arrows) in a 68-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. (c) Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images show soft-tissue infiltration of the mesenteric fat (arrowheads), as well as involvement of the renal fascia and lymphatics, which are highlighted and thickened (arrows) in an 81-year-old man with amyloidosis. (d) Coronal (top) and axial (bottom) contrast-enhanced CT images show infiltrative soft tissue in the retroperitoneum encasing the aorta (arrows) and associated with calcifications (arrowheads) in a 73-year-old man with amyloidosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig15d.jpeg" height="2080" width="1178" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span>. Manifestations of peritoneal and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in four patients. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows infiltrative soft-tissue and dystrophic calcifications (arrows) in the omentum and mesentery in a 70-year-old woman with AL amyloidosis, initially thought to represent peritoneal carcinomatosis. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows soft-tissue infiltration and thickening centered in the bilateral pelvic sidewall and presacral regions of the rectosigmoid mesentery with associated calcifications (arrows) in a 68-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. <b>(c)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced CT images show soft-tissue infiltration of the mesenteric fat (arrowheads), as well as involvement of the renal fascia and lymphatics, which are highlighted and thickened (arrows) in an 81-year-old man with amyloidosis. <b>(d)</b> Coronal (top) and axial (bottom) contrast-enhanced CT images show infiltrative soft tissue in the retroperitoneum encasing the aorta (arrows) and associated with calcifications (arrowheads) in a 73-year-old man with amyloidosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Evolution of mesenteric and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. (a, b) Axial (a)and coronal (b) contrast-enhanced CT images show diffuse infiltrative soft-tissue thickening in the mesentery bilateral perinephric and pararenal retroperitoneal spaces (arrows). (c, d) Axial (c) and coronal (d) contrast-enhanced CT images obtained 5 years later show extensive dystrophic calcification (arrows) of the infiltrative soft tissue, involving the mesentery and retroperitoneum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig16a.jpeg" height="824" width="1227" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Evolution of mesenteric and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show diffuse infiltrative soft-tissue thickening in the mesentery bilateral perinephric and pararenal retroperitoneal spaces (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial <b>(c)</b> and coronal <b>(d)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images obtained 5 years later show extensive dystrophic calcification (arrows) of the infiltrative soft tissue, involving the mesentery and retroperitoneum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic" aria-label="Evolution of mesenteric and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. (a, b) Axial (a)and coronal (b) contrast-enhanced CT images show diffuse infiltrative soft-tissue thickening in the mesentery bilateral perinephric and pararenal retroperitoneal spaces (arrows). (c, d) Axial (c) and coronal (d) contrast-enhanced CT images obtained 5 years later show extensive dystrophic calcification (arrows) of the infiltrative soft tissue, involving the mesentery and retroperitoneum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig16b.jpeg" height="1318" width="1227" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Evolution of mesenteric and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show diffuse infiltrative soft-tissue thickening in the mesentery bilateral perinephric and pararenal retroperitoneal spaces (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial <b>(c)</b> and co