ure id="fig16d" class="graphic" aria-label="Evolution of mesenteric and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. (a, b) Axial (a)and coronal (b) contrast-enhanced CT images show diffuse infiltrative soft-tissue thickening in the mesentery bilateral perinephric and pararenal retroperitoneal spaces (arrows). (c, d) Axial (c) and coronal (d) contrast-enhanced CT images obtained 5 years later show extensive dystrophic calcification (arrows) of the infiltrative soft tissue, involving the mesentery and retroperitoneum."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig16d.jpeg" height="1312" width="1222" aria-labelledby="fig16d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span>. Evolution of mesenteric and retroperitoneal amyloidosis in a 68-year-old man with AL amyloidosis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b>and coronal <b>(b)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show diffuse infiltrative soft-tissue thickening in the mesentery bilateral perinephric and pararenal retroperitoneal spaces (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial <b>(c)</b> and coronal <b>(d)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images obtained 5 years later show extensive dystrophic calcification (arrows) of the infiltrative soft tissue, involving the mesentery and retroperitoneum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig16d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="Wrist amyloid arthropathy involving the right carpal tunnel and carpal bones, manifesting as a soft-tissue mass in the volar wrist in a 65-year-old man with immunoglobulin A multiple myeloma and κ AL amyloidosis. (a, b) Axial T1-weighted (a) and corresponding proton-density–weighted fat-saturated (b) MR images show expansion of the carpal tunnel by synovial hypertrophy and low-signal-intensity soft-tissue infiltration (*), tenosynovitis involving the flexor and extensor compartments of the wrist (arrowheads), and slight flattening of the median nerve (arrows). (c) Intraoperative photograph (left) during right wrist flexor tenosynovectomy shows a coarse soft-tissue mass in the wrist (arrow). Illustration (right) shows the level of the carpal tunnel. (Illustration reprinted, with permission, from the Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.) (Case courtesy of Allen Bishop, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig17a.jpeg" height="1156" width="1087" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Wrist amyloid arthropathy involving the right carpal tunnel and carpal bones, manifesting as a soft-tissue mass in the volar wrist in a 65-year-old man with immunoglobulin A multiple myeloma and κ AL amyloidosis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted <b>(a)</b> and corresponding proton-density–weighted fat-saturated <b>(b)</b> MR images show expansion of the carpal tunnel by synovial hypertrophy and low-signal-intensity soft-tissue infiltration (*), tenosynovitis involving the flexor and extensor compartments of the wrist (arrowheads), and slight flattening of the median nerve (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph (left) during right wrist flexor tenosynovectomy shows a coarse soft-tissue mass in the wrist (arrow). Illustration (right) shows the level of the carpal tunnel. (Illustration reprinted, with permission, from the Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.) (Case courtesy of Allen Bishop, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic" aria-label="Wrist amyloid arthropathy involving the right carpal tunnel and carpal bones, manifesting as a soft-tissue mass in the volar wrist in a 65-year-old man with immunoglobulin A multiple myeloma and κ AL amyloidosis. (a, b) Axial T1-weighted (a) and corresponding proton-density–weighted fat-saturated (b) MR images show expansion of the carpal tunnel by synovial hypertrophy and low-signal-intensity soft-tissue infiltration (*), tenosynovitis involving the flexor and extensor compartments of the wrist (arrowheads), and slight flattening of the median nerve (arrows). (c) Intraoperative photograph (left) during right wrist flexor tenosynovectomy shows a coarse soft-tissue mass in the wrist (arrow). Illustration (right) shows the level of the carpal tunnel. (Illustration reprinted, with permission, from the Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.) (Case courtesy of Allen Bishop, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021210006/asset/images/large/rg.2021210006.fig17b.jpeg" height="1156" width="1166" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Wrist amyloid arthropathy involving the right carpal tunnel and carpal bones, manifesting as a soft-tissue mass in the volar wrist in a 65-year-old man with immunoglobulin A multiple myeloma and κ AL amyloidosis. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial T1-weighted <b>(a)</b> and corresponding proton-density–weighted fat-saturated <b>(b)</b> MR images show expansion of the carpal tunnel by synovial hypertrophy and low-signal-intensity soft-tissue infiltration (*), tenosynovitis involving the flexor and extensor compartments of the wrist (arrowheads), and slight flattening of the median nerve (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph (left) during right wrist flexor tenosynovectomy shows a coarse soft-tissue mass in the wrist (arrow). Illustration (right) shows the level of the carpal tunnel. (Illustration reprinted, with permission, from the Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and