xtensor compartments of the wrist (arrowheads), and slight flattening of the median nerve (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Intraoperative photograph (left) during right wrist flexor tenosynovectomy shows a coarse soft-tissue mass in the wrist (arrow). Illustration (right) shows the level of the carpal tunnel. (Illustration reprinted, with permission, from the Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research.) (Case courtesy of Allen Bishop, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021210006&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Howie AJ. Origins of a pervasive, erroneous idea: The “green birefringence” of Congo red-stained amyloid. <em>Int J Exp Pathol</em> 2019;100(4):208–221.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/iep.12330">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31515863/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Origins+of+a+pervasive%2C+erroneous+idea%3A+The+%E2%80%9Cgreen+birefringence%E2%80%9D+of+Congo+red-stained+amyloid&amp;author=AJ+Howie&amp;publication_year=2019&amp;journal=Int+J+Exp+Pathol&amp;pages=208-221&amp;doi=10.1111%2Fiep.12330&amp;pmid=31515863">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Benson MD, Buxbaum JN, Eisenberg DS, et al. Amyloid nomenclature 2020: update and recommendations by the International Society of Amyloidosis (ISA) nomenclature committee. <em>Amyloid</em> 2020;27(4):217–222.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/13506129.2020.1835263">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33100054/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Amyloid+nomenclature+2020%3A+update+and+recommendations+by+the+International+Society+of+Amyloidosis+%28ISA%29+nomenclature+committee&amp;author=MD+Benson&amp;author=JN+Buxbaum&amp;author=DS+Eisenberg&amp;publication_year=2020&amp;journal=Amyloid&amp;pages=217-222&amp;doi=10.1080%2F13506129.2020.1835263&amp;pmid=33100054">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Nomenclature of amyloid and amyloidosis. WHO-IUIS Nomenclature Sub-Committee. <em>Bull World Health Organ</em> 1993;71(1):105–112.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8440029/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Nomenclature+of+amyloid+and+amyloidosis.+WHO-IUIS+Nomenclature+Sub-Committee&amp;publication_year=1993&amp;journal=Bull+World+Health+Organ&amp;pages=105-112&amp;pmid=8440029">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Aterman K. A historical note on the iodine-sulphuric acid reaction of amyloid. <em>Histochemistry</em> 1976;49(2):131–143.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00495677">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/791904/">PubMed</a